	<article class="article ">
		<header class="block-content block-content-l1 block-content-center">
						<div class="block-content-header">
				<h6 class="b-content-section heading-square"><a href="/sections/essays-memoirs-true-stories">Essays, Memoirs, and True Stories</a></h6>
				<h1 class="block-content-title">Pilgrimage To Nowhere</h1>

				
				<ul class="block-content-meta list-inline-border tiny"><li>
							By <a class="meta-article-contributors" href="/contributors/andrew-boyd">Andrew Boyd</a></li><li><a href="/issues/389">May 2008</a></li></ul>

			</div>

																			

				<figure class="block-content-photo block-content-photo-large photo photo-outset-center-small">
					
					<img src="data:image/svg+xml;charset=utf-8,%3Csvg xmlns%3D'http%3A%2F%2Fwww.w3.org%2F2000%2Fsvg' viewBox%3D'0 0 1701 1960'%2F%3E"
		data-src=https://226391-691236-raikfcquaxqncofqfm.stackpathdns.com/thumbs/851x980r/photos/389-14-thomas.jpg data-src-retina=https://226391-691236-raikfcquaxqncofqfm.stackpathdns.com/thumbs/1701x1960r/photos/389-14-thomas.jpg
	 alt="389 - Thomas - Boyd"
	 class="lazy">

										<figcaption>

						
																				<div class="photo-credit">
								&copy;&nbsp;<a href="/contributors/kevin-thomas">Kevin Thomas</a>
							</div>
																		</figcaption>
									</figure>

					</header>

				<div class="article-body link-text-wrap">
																		<p><span class="dropcap">I</span>f spiritual seekers coming to Thailand were treated like their sex-tourist brethren, a contingent of saffron-robed monks would accost you at the Bangkok airport, getting up in your face with a laminated menu of spiritual offerings and shouting, &ldquo;Intensive Vipassana meditation! Twenty-one-day monastery stay! All-you-can-eat vegetarian meals! Hurt your knees! No sex! Donations only!&rdquo;</p>

<p>This was not the scene that confronted me on my arrival, but I did pick up a booklet from the International Buddhist Meditation Center in Bangkok, listing more than one hundred different temple stays, classes, and meditation retreats. At the boutique end of the spectrum was Wat Khao Tham, a Buddhist island retreat run by an expatriate Aussie American couple, complete with nearby spa, yoga workouts, and continental breakfasts. At the more austere end was the forest monastery of Wat Suan Mokkh, home temple of the late Buddhadasa Bhikkhu, a monk revered for his antimaterialism and rejection of worldly pleasures.</p>

<p>Bewildered by all the options, I got in touch with Joe Cummings, a friend of a friend and author of Lonely Planet&rsquo;s Thailand and Laos guidebooks. He recommended Doi Suthep monastery, which had a program for international students and a lineage tied to meditation master Ajaan Tong Sirimangalo.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Of course, it&rsquo;s been a few years since I&rsquo;ve been there,&rdquo; Joe added. &ldquo;Things change.&rdquo; I&rsquo;ve noticed that he and his Lonely Planet cohorts slip this disclaimer into every guidebook.</p>

<p>I contacted the monastery via e-mail. A message came back from one Phra Sam. <em>Phra </em>is Thai for &ldquo;monk&rdquo;; <em>Sam </em>is Canadian for &ldquo;Sam.&rdquo; He sent me an application form, which asked about my goals. Goals? <em>Annihilate my ego, such as it is</em>, I wanted to say (with the proviso that I could do this during an abbreviated ten-day stay and still make my next flight). Instead I wrote, &ldquo;To make compassion the source of my actions.&rdquo; I&rsquo;m not sure what I meant by this, but it got me in.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><span class="dropcap">I</span>t was late in the afternoon when I arrived at Doi Suthep. Saffron prayer flags fluttered in the breeze, slapping against the parking-lot lampposts. A few Thai families and several pairs of young European tourists were making their way up the final 108 steps to the hilltop temple and its four-hundred-year-old monastery. Some older and more-out-of-shape tourists were waiting for the elevator that had been installed the previous year. Pushcarts selling Buddhist paraphernalia were doing a brisk business. At the foot of the steps, a woman and her twin daughters were begging.</p>

<p>For the drive up from Chiang Mai, the nearest city, I&rsquo;d split a taxi with two young German women, one of whom was blond, cute, and sufficiently charmed with me to have more or less invited me back to the guesthouse where she&rsquo;d be staying that night &mdash; the same night that I, in a cruel twist of fate, would be putting on the white robes of an apprentice monk and swearing an oath of celibacy.</p>

<p>The two German tourists and I ascended the stairs together. They carried only water bottles and tiny shoulder bags; I had a full pack on. I could have taken the elevator, but it had occurred to me to make of these steps an impromptu minipilgrimage. I would squeeze the pilgrim&rsquo;s narrative into these 108 stairs &mdash; 108 being, according to Buddhist metaphysics, the number of difficulties to be overcome in the quest for enlightenment.</p>

<p>Over the previous four weeks I&rsquo;d tramped around Asia, visiting five countries. Now I was going to sit in one place for ten days and travel inward. Why? It was an experiment. I&rsquo;d come to Doi Suthep to see if I had the stuff that monks are made of.</p>

<p>When asked my religion on a form, I&rsquo;d check the box &ldquo;Other.&rdquo; If there was a blank line, I might write in, &ldquo;atheist with a vivid imagination,&rdquo; &ldquo;lapsed secular humanist,&rdquo; or simply, &ldquo;disorganized.&rdquo; But like any half-literate member of the counterculture, I was theoretically part Buddhist. In my salad days I&rsquo;d hitchhiked around the western United States, reading the Beats, <em>The Tao of Physics</em>, and <em>Zen and the Art of Motorcycle Maintenance</em>. I&rsquo;d parsed my acid experiences in the language of Jungian archetypes as well as Buddhist notions of maya, karma, and samsara. Decades later I&rsquo;d still turn out in the rain in Central Park to hear the Dalai Lama speak, and friends and I might exclaim, in the face of a perplexing yet paradoxically perfect moment, &ldquo;That&rsquo;s so Zen!&rdquo; But outside of a weekend stay at a meditation center here and there, I had never committed myself to a spiritual practice, instead pursuing a life of social activism and Abbie Hoffman&ndash;style political pranking.</p>

<p>And so I&rsquo;d come to Doi Suthep to see what would happen if I sat in silence day after day after day. Would I freak out? Would I go out of my head with boredom? Or would I burn away some of my vanity and walk out of this spiritual boot camp slightly more realized, slightly more adult?</p>

<p>As I neared the top of the stairs, my shoulders were hurting, and my calves were sore. As befits a pilgrim, I wore the sweat as a mark of virtue, and the pain felt almost purifying. Cresting the last stair &mdash; in effect, reaching the 108th and final stage of enlightenment &mdash; I arrived at a ticket window. The German women had to pay, while I, the apprentice-monk-to-be, got in free. My companions passed into the main monastery complex; I walked around the side toward the monks&rsquo; quarters. It was a separation of worlds: idle chatter and lovely blond temptress in one direction, silence and sublimated sexual desire in the other.</p>

<p>I was greeted by a bald, white-robed nun. Like a stern housekeeper she sized me up but betrayed no judgment. &ldquo;Phra Sam was expecting you earlier,&rdquo; she said with a thick German accent. &ldquo;He is not here now. Come.&rdquo; She led me down a concrete staircase, past a half-built dormitory &mdash; rebar poking up into the sky &mdash; and into a courtyard with scattered concrete benches and monks&rsquo; robes hanging on a clothesline, saffron yellow against the blue sky. A scruffy black dog crossed our path, and I stopped to scratch it behind the ears. <em>Am I doing this mindfully enough?</em> I wondered. <em>Can anyone tell?</em></p>

<p>She led me to a poorly lit meditation room and gave me a thin mat and several wool blankets with which to make a bed in the corner. The last meal of the day had already been eaten at 11 <span class="smallcaps">a.m.</span> The next meal would be at 6:30 the following morning. All apprentices were expected to rise at 4 <span class="smallcaps">a.m.</span> After breakfast, Phra Sam would conduct a vow-taking ceremony and give me my white apprentice robes. Until then I was to wear my whitest and loosest-fitting clothing.</p>

<p>After I&rsquo;d settled in, I went upstairs to a large meditation hall. The walls were white plaster, the window frames red and peeling, the wood floor stained an uneven blond. At one end was a Buddha shrine; at the other, a bank of fluorescent lights. I pulled a cushion under my butt, crossed my legs, cupped one hand inside the other just below my navel, and tried to quiet my mind. My thoughts, however, were anything but quiet. I&rsquo;d been jamming sights and sounds and smells into every sensory orifice for four weeks, and I had &ldquo;monkey mind&rdquo;: little gibbering creatures clambering all over the furniture inside my head. I couldn&rsquo;t help but wonder whether I&rsquo;d made a huge mistake. What was this place that I&rsquo;d come to, with its flickering fluorescent lights, clumsily carved Buddha statue, and damp-wool smell? And why was I taking ten days out of my grand Asian adventure to be frustrated by the everyday workings of my own thick head? Was I just another Western spiritual tourist, an experience junkie who had to try it all, a lost soul in search of some ill-defined notion of self &mdash; or no-self?</p>

<p>That night I had a dream: I was walking with the cute German tourist, who was pushing a stroller, &ldquo;practicing&rdquo; for when she had a kid. She was trying to get pregnant, she said, and I listened politely as she described her fucking schedule and fertility cycle. Instead of a baby in the carriage, there was a little Buddha.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><span class="dropcap">W</span>hen you join a Buddhist monastery &mdash; even as a Western apprentice monk who&rsquo;s just passing through &mdash; you take vows not to engage in sexual activity of any kind, not to steal, not to indulge in self-adornment or useless speech, and not to kill. There&rsquo;s an elaborate induction ceremony, which Phra Sam took me through that first morning. I had to repeat back a number of long, incomprehensible Thai and Pali sentences and prostrate myself to idols and personages I wasn&rsquo;t sure I believed in. My knees and ankles locked up as I bowed down to the plaster Buddha statuette. Then I scanned the fine print of the English translation of my vows, to see what I was getting myself into. I noticed that &ldquo;no sexual activity&rdquo; meant I couldn&rsquo;t talk to any of the nuns; &ldquo;no stealing&rdquo; meant I couldn&rsquo;t borrow anyone else&rsquo;s shampoo without asking; and &ldquo;no killing&rdquo; meant I couldn&rsquo;t even murder mosquitoes.</p>

<p>After the vow taking, I removed my two rings and the stud from my left ear. Phra Sam handed me a neatly folded pair of white drawstring pants and two front-buttoning white shirts: the &ldquo;robes&rdquo; that would mark me as an apprentice monk.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Are you clear on the practice?&rdquo; he asked.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Yes,&rdquo; I said. &ldquo;Well, no. Not completely.&rdquo;</p>

<p>He demonstrated how to do the walking meditation: slow, even footfalls, each step broken into three distinct parts. I followed his example, feeling silly. It seemed like a pantomime of walking.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Vipassana is insight meditation, the original teaching of the elders,&rdquo; said Sam, as he sat down in a meditation posture, indicating I should do the same. &ldquo;All suffering is the result of ignorance and attachment. We overcome this through the practice of mindfulness. When you meditate, thoughts and feelings will arise. Try to neither indulge them nor suppress them.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;The middle way.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Yes, in Vipassana we follow always the middle way.&rdquo;</p>

<p>I&rsquo;d heard that Phra Sam had been in a punk band in Canada. Bald, wiry, and pale, he still looked the part, only instead of combat boots and black leather, he wore flip-flops and the saffron robe of an ordained monk; and instead of a snarl, his lips were fixed in a slight smile. A sign of wisdom? Or a tic picked up at monk finishing school? I hoped it was the former.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Focus on the rising and falling of the abdomen,&rdquo; he instructed. &ldquo;Be mindful at all times. Always be<em> noticing .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. noticing</em>. When you&rsquo;re eating, be <em>chewing .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. chewing</em>. When brushing your teeth, be <em>brushing .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. brushing</em>.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Should I actually be saying, <em>Noticing .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. noticing</em>, in my mind?&rdquo; I asked.</p>

<p>Phra Sam&rsquo;s smile faded. &ldquo;Just BE <em>noticing .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. noticing</em>.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><span class="dropcap">I</span>f you&rsquo;ve never done it before, meditation is full of surprises. What should be the easiest thing in the world &mdash; sitting and breathing &mdash; is, in fact, excruciatingly difficult. My back grew sore, my knees cramped up, and my stomach trapped pockets of tension like gas bubbles. All the while my attention slipped into some ugly corner of my mind. A nasty radio interview from seven months earlier kept hijacking my thoughts. I&rsquo;d been ambushed by a right-wing talk-show host and his call-in cronies. Though I believed I had put the experience behind me, each time I assumed the sitting posture and began to breathe, <em>fwoosh</em>, there it was: the same shame and anger I&rsquo;d felt that day. I found myself spinning out revenge fantasies and rehearsing alternate comebacks that would have redeemed my dignity. Most disturbing was <em>noticing .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. noticing</em> my mind doing this. By whose orders had it developed these thoughts? By its own whims, it seemed. Who was &ldquo;I,&rdquo; then? (And what did &ldquo;I&rdquo; and my mind have in common?) Clich&eacute; stoner talk, for sure; fodder for late-night college bull sessions. But, observed up close and personal for ten hours a day, it was unsettling.</p>

<p>An apprentice monk&rsquo;s life is bound by routine and the walls of the monastery itself. We&rsquo;d wake at 4 <span class="smallcaps">a.m.</span> in darkness and silence. There was no Internet, no phone, no radio, no <span class="smallcaps">tv</span>, no movies, and no venturing off the grounds. The main temple &mdash; where relics were housed, rituals held, pilgrimages made, and favors granted &mdash; occupied the summit of the hill. With its stunning views, golden stupa, and carved roof gables, it drew the tourists. Just below the summit, spread along and down the hillside, were the monks&rsquo; quarters and meditation halls. Visitors might not notice our accommodations at all, yet it was impossible for us not to be aware of their presence. We&rsquo;d know they were on-site as soon as we heard the clanging bells: a set of ancient bronze bells, oxidized by the elements, were displayed alongside one of the monastery buildings, and a plaque informed visitors that they could ring the bells if they wished. The random and cacophonous clanging, like human-powered wind chimes, enveloped our daily meditations. The bells would start with the arrival of the first tourists at 9 <span class="smallcaps">a.m.</span> and wouldn&rsquo;t fall completely silent until the temple was closed to visitors at 6 <span class="smallcaps">p.m.</span></p>

<p>It was hard not to view the tourists with a certain condescension. They were just passing through, while we were here day after day. And we were <em>working</em>, even if our job description was &ldquo;Do nothing.&rdquo; What were they doing besides taking pictures and banging on bells?</p>

<p>Of course, this was high hypocrisy on my part. Had I not behaved just like them in a string of temples from Tokyo to Bangkok: admiring the architecture, peeking into hidden nooks and crannies, and observing the monks at work and leisure? Here at Doi Suthep it was <em>I</em> who was in the fishbowl. I was the freak in the religious theme park, an exotic <em>farang </em>&mdash; foreigner &mdash; in his white robes. After a month of being a tourist, I&rsquo;d finally put down anchor, only to become part of a tourist attraction.</p>

<p>One evening, after the tourists had left and the bells had gone quiet, I ascended to the temple and walked along its checkered marble patio. It was a glorious night: the stars above, the lights of Chiang Mai below, the rhythmic chanting of the monks filling the air. <em>Liking .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. liking</em>, I thought to myself, trying to notice my enjoyment without actually enjoying it. I fell into a conversation with three Thai monks who were in residence at Doi Suthep. Here were true-to-life Buddhist monks, draped in saffron, committed to the spiritual path, seasoned by years of meditation. I asked them how they had come here and how meditation had changed their lives.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Vipassana,&rdquo; said one, &ldquo;saved me from drink and migraines.&rdquo; The second said, &ldquo;Vipassana can make you rich. It can make you a better person, and more serious about work and family.&rdquo; The third remained behind after the other two had strolled off. He was younger than the others and had come to Doi Suthep as a boy. In broken English, he asked if I could help him get to the U.S.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><span class="dropcap">T</span>hough mealtimes were supposed to be silent, they were social occasions of a sort. At breakfast my first morning, a female apprentice with a ponytail handed me a plate and smiled. At the next meal, I helped her get a few slippery slices of mango into her bowl. &ldquo;Thanks,&rdquo; she said quietly. Given the isolation in which we spent most of our days, these felt like significant conversations. A few meals later Daniel, a skinny young man who seemed always to be smiling, took it upon himself to welcome me. Daniel had been in Thailand for five months and was to be ordained in a week or so. He said he&rsquo;d been practicing meditation for years back home in Wisconsin, yet he looked barely out of his teens.</p>

<p>One of the ten precepts we had all vowed to uphold was to refrain from taking meals after noon. Our 11 <span class="smallcaps">a.m.</span> lunch was therefore our last meal of the day. One morning at 11:50 I found myself sitting in the sunlit courtyard, looking at the remaining food on my plate the way a sailor might look at land before setting sail on a long ocean voyage. One bench over sat Silent Tim, a dour-looking monk who never spoke a word. Hannes, a new arrival from Austria, was sitting on the grass not far away. Dessert that day included a fruit I&rsquo;d never seen before. Its white and pink flesh was flecked with tiny black seeds, and it melted in my mouth with a taste and texture somewhere between watermelon and mango.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Do you know what this is?&rdquo; I asked Hannes.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Dragon fruit,&rdquo; he whispered back.</p>

<p>Hannes was in his early thirties and handsome, with the air of someone bemused by the universe: not quite sure what it was all about, but not overly concerned about it either. I liked him immediately.</p>

<p>&ldquo;What does dragon fruit look like before it&rsquo;s cut up?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Like one of those spiked medieval clubs,&rdquo; he answered. &ldquo;Ironic, yah?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Ah, glasshoppah,&rdquo; I whispered back, &ldquo;irony of nature is gateway to wisdom.&rdquo;</p>

<p>He placed his hands together and bowed. &ldquo;We must all be like dee suttuhl dlagon fluit.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><span class="dropcap">&ldquo;A</span>ny questions about the practice?&rdquo; Phra Sam asked at my daily reporting session.</p>

<p>&ldquo;May I meditate in the garden?&rdquo; I asked.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Yes.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;If I wear socks, must they also be white?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;That won&rsquo;t be necessary.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Why do you have us focus on just the rising and falling of the abdomen and not the full path of the breath?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Because that&rsquo;s how we do it here.&rdquo;</p>

<p><em>OK,</em> <em>fine</em>. &ldquo;When meditating, how do I relax while also exerting a focused effort?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Ah, that <em>is </em>the question.&rdquo; Phra Sam seemed pleased. This was more what he had in mind. &ldquo;It takes mindfulness, patience, and time,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;Now, I have a question for you: When you&rsquo;re walking, are the left and right foot separate, or one?&rdquo;</p>

<p>Finally, the Vipassana equivalent of a Zen koan. I said nothing, just bowed my head in the wisest way I knew how and let my silence speak for itself.</p>

<p>Phra Sam arched his eyebrows. &ldquo;Separate or one?&rdquo; he asked again.</p>

<p><em>Mu</em>, I wanted to say, a Japanese word that means neither yes nor no. I waited for him to hit me with a big stick. &ldquo;Well, both, I guess. Sort of.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;One ends in the mind before the other begins, yes?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Uh, <span class="smallcaps">ok</span>.&rdquo; I had no idea what he was driving at, and he didn&rsquo;t seem particularly happy with me either.</p>

<p>&ldquo;So, separate or one?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Um, I&rsquo;m not trying to be difficult, but .&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Fine,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;Do twenty minutes: twenty minutes walking, twenty minutes sitting.&rdquo; The reporting session was over, the recruit dismissed.</p>

<p>As I headed back to the upper meditation hall, a mournful temple dog stared out from a shaded doorstep. I noticed how ragged the garden was: its pond thick with algae; the elephant sculpture weathered, the cracks in its concrete head filled with mortar. I felt homeless. <em>What is this place?</em> I thought. <em>What am I doing here?</em> A throng of saffron-clad child monks, their classes over for the day, were playing ping-pong. An elderly nun was sweeping the concrete pathways, wielding two short-handled brooms, one in each hand, as if they were swords.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><span class="dropcap">H</span>ot chocolate was the one luxury we were permitted. You made it yourself with a combination of boiling water, mysterious bulk chocolate powder, powdered milk, copious amounts of sugar, and &mdash; if you wanted to be spiritually correct &mdash; no ants. You had to blow the ants (nonviolently, of course) off each of the tins before opening them. As I assembled my drink at the close of lunch, I had to blow three times for each tin, harder each time, saying, <em>Blowing .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. blowing</em>, to myself. I noticed Smiling Daniel, empty mug in hand, looking at my strenuous efforts and smiling even more than usual.</p>

<p>&ldquo;These ants have extremely good traction,&rdquo; I whispered. He nodded. He was a lanky, yet somehow graceful, twenty-year-old with angelic good looks. His viking mop of blond hair had been shaved off the day before, leaving a stubbly pate, as well as a gash where our cook&rsquo;s razor had gone awry.</p>

<p>&ldquo;How&rsquo;s the practice going?&rdquo; he asked. He made it sound like the next reality <span class="smallcaps">tv</span> show: <em>The Practice</em> &mdash; five monks in an inner-city Zen center; their lives, their loves, their quest for self-annihilation.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Oh, up and down,&rdquo; I said. &ldquo;This morning some good progress, but earlier today and yesterday I was pretty upset. You create all this empty space, and all kinds of stuff comes up to fill it.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;That shows you&rsquo;re really practicing, if stuff is coming up.&rdquo;</p>

<p>I told him I was also having trouble with a lot of Buddhist metaphysics. The whole rebirth thing, for one, didn&rsquo;t seem consistent. Hadn&rsquo;t the Buddha broken with the earlier Vedic philosophy around the notion of a permanent soul? So what was there to be reborn? In Buddhism, as I understood it, self and soul were illusions, like everything else.</p>

<p>&ldquo;There&rsquo;s no personality that gets reborn,&rdquo; Smiling Daniel said. &ldquo;But there&rsquo;s a see-er, a place from which to gaze. That does get reborn.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;That&rsquo;s pretty deep for a twenty-year-old with no hair.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Smiling Daniel smiled.</p>

<p>&ldquo;When I try to bring any of this up with Phra Sam, I get nowhere,&rdquo; I said.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Yeah, he doesn&rsquo;t know anything.&rdquo;</p>

<p>I was unsure how to respond. I agreed, or thought I did, but was surprised to hear it so baldly stated. &ldquo;But at least he&rsquo;s a decent teacher,&rdquo; I said.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Actually, no, he&rsquo;s terrible. He teaches beginners and those with ten years&rsquo; experience the same way. You know the book he&rsquo;s got?&rdquo; I remembered a little notebook he always had at his side during reporting sessions. It reminded me of a grading book. &ldquo;That&rsquo;s the regime. He just insists on that. You can&rsquo;t teach that way. I was reporting to him the other day, telling him about an insight I&rsquo;d had about the nature of thought behind the thinking, and it wasn&rsquo;t in the book, so he couldn&rsquo;t handle it. He cut me off: &lsquo;When you&rsquo;re thinking, just be <em>thinking .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. thinking</em>. Do thirty minutes walking, thirty minutes sitting. Now go practice.&rsquo;&nbsp;&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;He did that to me too.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;He has a temper. He&rsquo;s insecure. He knows all the terms and all the stories, but it&rsquo;s as if he hasn&rsquo;t meditated.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Well,&rdquo; I said, &ldquo;it seems I&rsquo;m not crazy, after all. I can&rsquo;t tell you how I&rsquo;ve been ping-ponging back and forth in my head for days: <em>Am I totally arrogant? Is he a fraud? Am I the only one who&rsquo;s feeling this way?</em>&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Kind of helps that none of us apprentices can talk to each other, huh?&rdquo; As if we were a comic duo, we both turned from side to side, pretending to look out for the monastery secret police.</p>

<p>Smiling Daniel said he was just going through the motions to get his ordination. He was a week away from completing his full twenty-one-day course, after which he hoped to be accepted into the <em>sangha</em>, the great community of monks. He would leave Doi Suthep and wander from monastery to monastery in his saffron robes. He could ride buses for free, and people would put food in his begging bowl.</p>

<p>&ldquo;So, listen,&rdquo; I said, &ldquo;now that I&rsquo;ve got you here &mdash; a knowledgeable person I can actually talk to and all &mdash; when you&rsquo;re doing walking meditation, are your feet one or separate?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;One <em>and </em>separate.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Right! That&rsquo;s exactly what I&rsquo;ve been thinking.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;You should talk to Roger about all this.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Roger?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Yeah. Big bald guy. You&rsquo;ve seen him getting lunch with us sometimes.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Oh, yeah, him.&rdquo; I remembered him from the food line the day before: a big-chested, bullet-headed man in his early fifties. He&rsquo;d ladled his rice and vegetable curry with slow, controlled movements, his eyes grinning. &ldquo;What&rsquo;s his story?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;He&rsquo;s the resident philosopher dude. He runs the information center: does drop-in meditation demos and teaches Buddhist-philosophy courses.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;He&rsquo;s not a monk?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;No. &lsquo;I have enough precepts of my own,&rsquo; he told me. &lsquo;I don&rsquo;t need theirs too.&rsquo;&nbsp;&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;He sounds like the man to see.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;He&rsquo;s cool, but the real man to see is Ajaan Tong.&rdquo; Smiling Daniel explained that Ajaan Tong &mdash; the teacher of all the teachers and the true master of the monastery &mdash; resided at Chom Tong, another monastery several miles south.</p>

<p>I thanked Smiling Daniel, who dipped his head to me, and we went our separate ways. Things at Doi Suthep were becoming clearer and murkier in equal measure. With each revelation, it seemed, a new intrigue was added. The next day I would go see this philosopher, Roger, and maybe later in the week, if I could, Ajaan Tong. Until then I was more or less on my own.</p>

<p><figure class="photo photo-outset-center-medium">
	<div>
					<div>
				<img src="data:image/svg+xml;charset=utf-8,%3Csvg xmlns%3D'http%3A%2F%2Fwww.w3.org%2F2000%2Fsvg' viewBox%3D'0 0 1960 1582'%2F%3E"
